snippet.textDisplay: I think it's time Davis put his pugilist skills to the test with the best at 135, I understand the politics of a mandatory challenger to the title you hold and the rankings vary based on the title and the commission it's under. Big problem with this sport, is the amount of belts, i think it should be scaled down to two or three, more so two titles per division that's it; it's a marketing ploy how many titles there are. They create new titles each day...Tank has the pop and the speed, but he'll need to tone down his aggressive assaults with a more skilled fighter or fighters, and become more a Floyd type counter puncher with great defense later in his career, Tank just has more pop in his shots which means he could also systematically break opponents down and finish/ko/stop them, as opposed to his all out attack, he finishes well when he has his man hurt. Looking forward to seeing who he faces next, hopefully a class A or B fighter, I believe Tank is 25 years of age and hasn't been in many wars he's very well prepared to take on the top fighters now and we shall truly see if he is this phenom Floyd Mayweather Jr. makes him out to be.

Tank is young and obviously loves the lifestyle of a high profile entertainer and he will learn in time what’s good for his body to last long in the sport. I mean for gods sakes, Floyd would go straight to the boxing gym right after a 2am club night but again we are talking levels dedication and greatness and Floyd’s sits on that hill alone among all top athletes beside Michael Jordan. Tank will either have nature remind him to be more professional about his craft that helps feed his family or he will let Floyd’s advice take heed.
